Amend the European stability pact
The European stability pact, which underpins the euro by establishing constraints determining the size of budget deficits of Union members, is in danger.
Germany, the backbone of the Union, failed to uphold its budgetary commitments to its European partners.
In addition, she used her political weight to cover the early warning signal of her deficit, established by the European Commission under the terms of the stability pact.
Today it is France that is playing the bad guy.
The second-ranking figure of the Union, somewhat reluctant, has now officially declared that he cannot uphold his deficit reduction commitment, a year after the small Ireland received an official warning regarding its fiscal policies, despite its budget surpluses, and in a very severe manner.
Thus, four years after its signing, the stability pact is a real disaster.
In fact, Europe seems very affected by the discussions aimed at eliminating it, as well as the discussions aimed at amending it.
And rightly so: the pact is poorly designed and its implementation poorly carried out.
The limit on the deficit to 3% of GDP is arbitrary and ignores the fact that deficits automatically increase when the economy slows down.
Assuming this is true, the architects of the pact worsened the situation by adopting two "poorly thought-out" solutions.
They introduced a safety clause allowing any country to suspend its deficit limits in case of a severe recession, but they defined it in such a way that any suspension was practically impossible in fact.
Concerned that serious slowdowns could undermine the deficit ceiling, they decreed that a normal deficit equaled zero deficit.
Thus, each year, each country must submit a budget forecast for the next two years demonstrating how the budget balance will be achieved in due time.
The German commitment for 2002 was made in 2001, when its economy was developing at a reasonable pace.
The unexpected slowdown prevents Germany from achieving its goals.
The finance minister, Hans Eichel, reasonably decided not to worsen the situation by adopting a contractionary fiscal policy.
The Commission, seeking to position itself as the protector of the pact, wanted to issue a warning, but this decision had to be made by real politicians, the Council of Finance Ministers.
No one wanted to embarrass Germany since everyone recognized they could face the same problem in the future.
Thus, no warning was issued.
The situation in France is different.
During election periods, politicians inevitably make promises, including tax burden reduction.
In a country where the tax burden is significant, it is not only a matter of political intelligence but also economic intelligence, as long as budget expenditures are also reduced.
However, France is also a country where everyone benefits from certain privileges financed by the state, and therefore, budget cuts are definitively poorly perceived.
Thus, France cannot meet its targets, and the Commission expressed its frustration.
But France has mastered the art of defying the laws of the Union.
Political maneuvering will inevitably follow.
Economists and cynics are not greatly surprised.
The objective of the pact, to establish fiscal discipline within countries sharing the same currency, is entirely justified.
However, the loss of control over their national monetary policy, Union members are left with only one macroeconomic tool: fiscal policies.
The challenge is therefore to combine long-term discipline with short-term flexibility.
Just like promising to go on a diet before a big party, this challenge is not easy to reconcile.
The stability pact is too rudimentary and technocratic: the objective of the 3% set by Brussels bureaucrats cannot bind politicians in office.
The solution must be found elsewhere.
Fortunately, we don't have to look far.
Monetary policy faces the same challenge.
It must stabilize prices in the long term while remaining sufficiently flexible in the short term to manage economic cycles.
Over the past ten years, monetary policy experienced real success.
The recipe is the same everywhere: it suffices to delegate this policy to a competent group, the Central Bank, by granting it the necessary political independence and a clear and well-defined mandate.
Knowing that any misstep will have to be addressed in the future, it is up to him to exercise good judgment.
This proved to be one of the major improvements in the monetary field in recent years.
The same approach should work for fiscal policy.
Some fear, of course, to lose out on democracy.
It is essential to understand that fiscal policy serves two very different purposes.
The first is structural and redistributive and concerns the importance of the budget and its detailed structure in terms of both expenditures and revenues.
Decisions on these matters cannot be delegated and must remain in the hands of elected governments, subject to parliamentary approval and oversight.
The second is macroeconomic: it involves defining the budget balance to manage economic fluctuations.
It does not differ much from monetary policy and can be delegated to an independent body.
Thus, Europe's task is clear.
Each country must regain full control of its fiscal policies but delegate its macroeconomic components, its decisions on deficits or surpluses, to an independent Fiscal Policy Committee whose long-term objective is the stabilization (or reduction, for some countries) of public debt.
To ensure its effectiveness, the status and mandates of such a Committee must be subject to a consensus within the Union, without any interference from Brussels, without any arbitrary rulings, without any political decision-making, but simply by relying on common sense.
